1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. c3 c5 6. Bd3 Nc6 7. Ngf3 {In this
line White is often ready to ruin his pawn chain for an initiative.} (7. Ne2 {
is more popular and positionally sound line.}) 7... g6 $5 {This is a
relatively rare line. The main continuation is 7...Qb6 attacking the Pd4.} 8.
h4 {The move 7...g6 gave White a target and he reacts accordingly. Both
players have experience in this line.} Qb6 (8... h6 9. Bc2 b5 10. O-O a5 11.
Re1 cxd4 12. cxd4 g5 13. Nf1 g4 14. N3h2 h5 15. g3 Qb6 16. Be3 Bb4 17. Re2 Ba6
18. Rc1 O-O-O 19. f3 gxf3 20. Nxf3 $14 {1-0 Adams,M (2729)-Berg,E (2593)/Crete
2007/CBM 121 (48)}) (8... Be7 9. O-O h6 (9... Bxh4 10. Nxh4 Qxh4 11. Nf3 Qg4
12. Be2 $44 {Gurevich,M}) 10. Re1 cxd4 (10... c4 $5 11. Bc2 Bxh4 12. Nxh4 Qxh4
$13 {Navara}) 11. cxd4 Bxh4 12. Nxh4 Qxh4 13. Nf3 Qe7 14. Be3 Nb6 15. Rc1 Bd7
16. a3 O-O-O 17. b4 Kb8 18. Bd2 $1 {[%cal Gb4b5]} a6 19. b5 axb5 20. Bxb5 $36 {
1/2-1/2 Navara,D (2602)-Gurevich,M (2672)/Antalya 2004/CBM 101/[Gurevich,M] 
(75)}) 9. dxc5 $6 {In my opinion, this move is not in the spirit of the
position. 9.h5 is more consistent.} (9. h5 g5 $1 {Black must not open the
h-file.} 10. Nxg5 cxd4 11. cxd4 Qxd4 (11... Nxd4 12. Ndf3 Nxf3+ 13. Nxf3 h6 14.
O-O Qb4 15. Be3 Nc5 16. Nd4 Nxd3 17. Qxd3 Bd7 18. b3 Bg7 19. f4 $14 {1-0
Smirin,I (2691)-Gurevich,M (2688)/Dos Hermanas 2001/CBM 083 (55)}) 12. Ndf3
Qb4+ 13. Bd2 Qxb2 14. Bxh7 Ndxe5 15. Rb1 Qxa2 (15... Qa3 $5 {might be an
improvement.}) 16. Nxe5 Nxe5 17. Bc3 Bg7 18. O-O Qc4 19. h6 Bf6 20. Bxe5 Bxe5
21. Qh5 Rxh7 22. Nxh7 Bf4 23. Nf6+ Ke7 24. h7 {1-0 Babaev,R (2468)-Medghoul,S 
(2231)/Cappelle La Grande FRA 2008/The Week in Chess 694}) 9... Qc7 $1 {
Correct. The Pe5 is more important to capture.} (9... Bxc5 10. Qe2 Qc7 11. Nb3
Bb6 12. Bf4 f6 13. O-O-O Ndxe5 14. Kb1 {with a strong initiative for the pawn.
[%cal Gh1e1]}) 10. Nb3 Ndxe5 11. Nxe5 (11. h5 Bg7 (11... Nxf3+ $6 12. Qxf3 Ne5
13. Bb5+ Bd7 14. Bxd7+ {and Black has to recapture with the king to avoid the
worst.}) 12. Bc2 O-O 13. Qe2 b6 {Black is okay in this case as well. White is
not able to increase pressure along the h-file.}) 11... Nxe5 12. O-O Nxd3 (
12... Bxc5 $6 13. Nxc5 Qxc5 14. Be3 {is not recommended for Black. The weak
dark squares in his camp are worth more than a pawn.}) 13. Qxd3 Bg7 14. h5 O-O
{Black should be satisfied with the results of the opening. He has pair of
bishops and potentially strong pawns in the centre. Meanwhile, White's
benefits are not so clear.} 15. Bg5 b6 {Opening space for the light-squared
bishop.} 16. h6 $1 {This annoying pawn gives White some attacking chances in
the long run.} Bh8 17. cxb6 axb6 18. Rfe1 Bb7 {Protecting Pd5 in order to be
able to push forward the e-pawn.} 19. Nd4 e5 20. Nb5 Qc6 21. a4 f6 (21... d4
22. f3 e4 23. Qxe4 (23. fxe4 $6 Qc5 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Gd4c3]}) 23... Qxe4 24.
fxe4 dxc3 25. Nxc3 Rfe8 $11) 22. Bd2 f5 23. f4 $1 {White's only play is all
around the dark squares.} d4 24. Qf1 dxc3 $6 {This helps White to activate his
bishop.} (24... exf4 25. Nxd4 Bxd4+ 26. cxd4 g5 $15 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Gc6h6]})
25. Bxc3 exf4 26. Bxh8 Kxh8 {[%csl Gh6,Rh8]} 27. Rac1 {After the exchange of
dark-squared bishops Black's monarch is in danger.} Qf6 28. Qxf4 Qxb2 29. Qe5+
$1 {Eliminating the key defender.} (29. Re2 Qf6 30. Rc7 Bd5 {and White has no
real threats.}) 29... Qxe5 30. Rxe5 {Objectively, Black's position is still
okay. However, it was obviously difficult for Navara to handle this position
in time trouble. Black has to watch out for both the 8th and 7th ranks.} Rxa4
$2 (30... Rfd8 $1 {preventing the knight moves.} 31. Re7 Bd5 32. Rcc7 Bg8 $11)
31. Nd6 Rd4 (31... Ba8 $1 32. Rc7 Rh4 33. Rf7 Rg8 {Now, White can achieve
either an extra piece, or an exchange, but both endgames should be drawn:} 34.
Ne8 (34. Rg7 Rxh6 35. Rxg8+ Kxg8 36. Re8+ Kg7 37. Rxa8) 34... Bd5 35. Rfe7 Bc4
36. Nf6 Rxh6 37. Nxg8 Bxg8 38. Rb7 g5 39. Rxf5 Rg6) 32. Rc7 (32. Nxb7 $2 Rd7 {
trapping the knight.}) 32... Bd5 (32... Rxd6 $2 33. Ree7 {mating.}) 33. Rd7 Kg8
$2 {The final mistake.} ({It was necessary to sacrifice an exchange:} 33... Bc6
34. Nf7+ Kg8 35. Rxd4 Kxf7 36. Rd6 Rc8 {still keeping reasonable chances for a
draw.}) 34. Re8 (34. Ne8 $1 {was even more devastating, as the mating threat
35.Rg7+ followed by 36.Nf6 Rxf6 37.Re8 mate, is unanswerable.}) 34... Rxe8 35.
Nxe8 Rd1+ 36. Kh2 Bb3 (36... Kf8 37. Nf6 $18) 37. Nf6+ {Ideal coordination
between White's forces.} Kf8 38. Nxh7+ Ke8 39. Nf6+ Kf8 40. h7 {Impressive
play by Mickey Adams!} 1-0

