1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. c3
d6 9. h3 Bb7 10. d4 Re8 11. Nbd2 Bf8 12. d5 Nb8 13. Nf1 Nbd7 14. N3h2 Nc5 15.
Bc2 c6 16. b4 Ncd7 17. dxc6 Bxc6 18. Bg5 h6 19. Bxf6 Nxf6 20. Ng4 Nxg4 21. Qxg4
Rc8 22. Bb3 Bd7 23. Qf3 Be6 24. Red1 Qg5 {Adams remains faithfull to the plan
designed by him and successfully employed in Wijk aan Zee 2008.} 25. Rd3 Qf4
26. Qe2 Bxb3 27. axb3 d5 28. exd5 $5 $146 ({After the overcautious} 28. Rxd5 {
Leko,P (2753)-Adams,M (2726)/Wijk aan Zee 2008/CBM 122/[Marin] (1/2-1/2, 98).
White's advantage will be microscopical.}) 28... e4 29. Re3 Qe5 30. Rxa6 f5 31.
Ng3 (31. Qxb5 f4 32. Re2 Rxc3 $44) 31... Qxd5 (31... Rxc3 $2 32. Rxc3 Qxc3 33.
Nxf5 $16) (31... Bxb4 32. Nxf5 $1 (32. cxb4 $2 f4 33. Rxe4 Rc1+) 32... Qxf5 33.
cxb4 Qxd5 34. Rg3 $16) 32. Qh5 {In my comments for CBM 122 I had reached this
position, with the following conclusion: "Here, we can see a drawback of the
move ...h6: with the pawn on h7, Black wouls simply play ...g6. Well, there is
no such thing as the perfect move, especially when you play with black. Anyway,
only further practical testing will reveal the objective merits of Adams' plan.
" I believe that even after this game, the question remains open.} Re5 33. Qg6
Qf7 {An important move. Black needs to unblock the g6-square in order to
re-establish the flexibility and intergrity of his kingside structure.} ({After
} 33... f4 34. Nxe4 Be7 35. Re1 Rxc3 {Black's pieces would be hanging and
White would dispose over several promissing continuation. Personally, I like}
36. Rf6 $5 {most. White will win the f4-pawn.}) 34. Qxf7+ Kxf7 35. Ra7+ Be7 {
It is not easy to take a decision regarding the king's placement.} (35... Kf6
$6 {allows White win time for the activation of his knight with} 36. Nh5+ Kg6 (
36... Kg5 $2 37. f4+ $1 $18) 37. Nf4+ $16) ({I believe that} 35... Ke6 {would
be better than the game continuation.} 36. Ne2 (36. Nh5 g5) 36... Kf6 37. Ra6+
Re6 $1 {(Maintaining the king active despite a new material loss.)} 38. Rxe6+
Kxe6 39. Nd4+ Ke5 40. Nxb5 f4 41. Re1 Ra8 42. Kf1 g5 $44 {It is quite obvious
that Black's position is much more active than that reached in the game after
the first time control.}) 36. Ne2 Ke8 37. Rb7 Rd5 38. Nd4 Bg5 39. Rxb5 Rxb5 40.
Nxb5 Rb8 (40... Bxe3 41. Nd6+ Kd7 42. Nxc8 Bxf2+ 43. Kxf2 Kxc8 {does not offer
hopes.} 44. Ke3 g6 45. c4 Kc7 46. b5 Kb6 47. b4 {and Black will fall victim of
successive zugzwang positions.} Kb7 48. c5) 41. Nc7+ {"Obviously", White has
find a way to save his attacked pieces. However, the method chosen by him in
the game will allow Black activate his king.} ({After} 41. Nd6+ $5 Kd7 42. Nxf5
Bxe3 43. fxe3 $16 {White has 3 pawns for the exchange and the enemy kingside
is vulnerable.}) 41... Kd7 42. Na6 Ra8 43. Nc5+ Kc6 44. Re2 Ra1+ 45. Kh2 Kb5
46. Rc2 Bf6 47. g3 Rd1 48. Kg2 Be5 $14 {Black is very active now and can hope
to reach a draw.} 49. h4 g6 50. Ne6 Rd6 $6 (50... Rd3 $1 {may have saved a
tempo.}) 51. Nf4 Bxf4 52. gxf4 Rd3 {[%cal Gd3f3,Gf3f4,Gh6h5]} ({As we shall
see later,} 52... h5 {would be useful in certain cases, but here there is no
time for it:} 53. Re2 $1 Rd3 54. Re3 Rd2 55. Rg3 Rd6 56. Kf1 $18) 53. c4+ $1 {
The only chance to play for a win.} Kxb4 54. c5 Kxb3 55. Rc1 Kb2 (55... Rd7 56.
c6 Rc7 57. h5 $1 gxh5 58. Kh3 $18 {is similar to the game.}) 56. Rc4 Rd7 $2 {
After this move, Black will lose by force.} ({The only saving chance would
have been} 56... Kb3 57. c6 $1 {(the only way to avoid immediate draw by
repetition)} Rd8 $1 58. c7 Rc8 59. Rc6 Kb4 $1 (59... h5 {allows White activate
his king with} 60. f3 exf3+ 61. Kxf3 Kb4 62. Ke3 Kb5 63. Rc1 Kb6 64. Kd4 $18)
60. Rxg6 (60. f3 {is too slow now:} exf3+ 61. Kxf3 Kb5 62. Rc1 $6 Kb6 63. Ke3
